    "Model Choice": "A physics-informed neural network (PINN) is appropriate because it can directly incorporate the PDE residuals, boundary conditions, and incompressibility as soft constraints. The model outputs (u,v,p,T) as functions of (x,y,t). A fully connected neural network with residual connections (e.g., modified MLP) is chosen to handle the multi-scale nature of boundary layers. Hard constraints: incompressibility can be enforced via a streamfunction formulation (u = ∂ψ/∂y, v = -∂ψ/∂x) to exactly satisfy ∇·u=0, reducing outputs to ψ, p, T. This avoids a separate divergence loss. The network must be deep enough (e.g., 8-10 layers, 128 neurons) to capture sharp gradients near walls. Activation: tanh for smooth derivatives. The model is trained on collocation points sampled adaptively near boundaries and in the bulk.",
